{"title":"Unlocking Speech Instruction Data Potential with Query Rewriting","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"Validating that TTS-synthesized speech preserves the linguistic content of the source text is unreliable with a single ASR or WER-only checks; ASR errors lead to improper filtering and dataset bias.","method":"Use multi-agent annotation and verification: transcribe each synthesized audio with three diverse ASR models (whisper-large-v3, canary-1b, parakeet-tdt-1.1b) and compute semantic similarity to the original text using three embedding models (gte-large-en-v1.5, mxbai-embed-large-v1, stella_en_400M_v5). Average across ASRs and embeddings to form a SIM score and filter with a threshold (α=0.9). This ensemble reduces annotation errors and aligns well with WER (e.g., >98% consistency when WER=0) and improves WER over single-ASR selection (Table 4)."},{"problem":"Modern TTS struggles with out-of-distribution instruction text (e.g., abbreviations, numerals, formulas), causing loss of linguistic information and limiting scalable construction of speech-instruction datasets without human annotation.","method":"Apply multi-LLM zero-shot query rewriting to fit TTS training distributions: generate candidate rewrites with Llama-3-8B-Instruct, Phi-3-small-8k-instruct, and Qwen2-7B-Instruct; synthesize speech for each candidate (using ParlerTTS with 192 GPT-4-generated speaker style descriptions or fixed-voice MeloTTS/MMS-TTS); score each audio via the multi-agent SIM metric and select the best pair for training. This boosts average semantic similarity from 93.06% to 97.98% and data usability (Pass≥0.9) from ~72% to ~93%, and narrows quality gaps across TTS backends (Table 2)."},{"problem":"Challenging rewrites that require complex, context-dependent knowledge remain difficult; different LLMs exhibit complementary strengths leading to failures on a subset of queries.","method":"Perform knowledge fusion for rewriting: collect pairs of original text and the best rewrite that significantly improves SIM (q(A,E|ĉ,c)>α), fine-tune Meta-Llama-3-8B-Instruct with LoRA on these pairs to distill complementary rewriting knowledge, then re-rewrite failed samples and reselect via SIM. This yields consistent gains over the no-fusion variant across single- and multi-speaker settings (Table 2) and improves handling of context-aware and knowledge-intensive rewrites (case studies)."}]}
